%N A089280 Tower of Hanoi game: a(n) is the number of pegs occupied by already-moved disks after move #n.
%C A089280 A001511 states the disk number moved on the n-th move.
%C A089280 A035263 indicates the direction of the n-th move (clockwise or not).
%D A089280 Gary W. Adamson in "Beyond Measure, A Guided Tour Through Nature, Myth and Number" by Jay Kappraff, World Scientific, 2002, Chapter 15, "Number: Gray Code and the Towers of Hanoi", Table 15.1, p. 341-342.
%H A089280 <a href="/index/To#Hanoi">Index entries for sequences related to Towers of Hanoi</a>
%F A089280 Write n in binary; count the length of each span of equal bits. (25 -> 11001 -> 2, 2, 1.) If there is one span, a(n)=1. Otherwise, ignore the first and last spans: a(n)=3 if an odd span-length remains; a(n)=2 if not.
%e A089280 a(25)=2 because after 25 moves, 2 pegs have disks (2&3, -, 1&4&5).
%Y A089280 Cf. A001511, A035263.
%K A089280 nonn
%O A089280 1,2
